of the hardworking, innovative American creator. The Color of Creatorship contributes to a rapidly-developing conversation in critical race intellectual property. Vats argues that once anti-racist activists grapple with the underlying racial structures of intellectual property law, they can better advocate for strategies that resist the underlying drivers of racially disparate copyright, patent, and trademark policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aIntellectual propertyxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aRace discriminationxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 7aLAW / Intellectual Property / General.2bisacsh  acopyright.  aintellectual property rights.  apatent.  arace.  aracial scripts.  atrademark.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069218140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361096540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503610965423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503610965/original  a978-3-11-069218-1  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles